@TomFenech, `echo -e "test 1"` doesn't contain any backslash escapes at all, so since the OP claims to actually need `-e`, presumably their real code/situation is more interesting. If they have content with literal escapes in a variable and they want to print that variable with those escapes evaluated, you wouldn't want any `%`s in the variable to be treated as substitution placeholders, hence `%b` (honoring backslashes, but not `%` expansion placeholders).
